@node "Intro" "Introduction"
Why WebView?  Why write a Web Document Previewer when there are plenty of
good Amiga Web Browsers out there?  AMosaic, IBrowse, AWeb, Voyager...the
list goes on.  Why, John?  Why?  Why did you write us a Doc Previewer? Why?

Well, to be perfectly honest, I can't afford squat.  On my $20 a week
allowance, its impossible to save for a License Permit Test, let alone
AmigaDos 3.1.  I have 2.1, but only AMosaic 1.2 runs on that, and it really
sucks (sorry, Omnipresence).  Plus, it only handles the bare minimum of HTML
tags, nothing cool like Backgrounds or Tables or Color Fonts.  I wanted
something to look at my Web Pages on, and WebView was written.

Of course, my first attempts were pure cheesiness.  No header fonts, no cool
fonts period, no working ARexx port, no NOTHING!  I knew that, if I wanted
WebView to be noticed, it would have to kick serious butt.  And besides,
Amos ate my original.  It wouldn't compile anymore.  Again, all my problems
go back to François Lionet.

WebView has it all.  I have tested many pages on both Microsoft Internet
Explorer and WebView. Except for a few differences in Table handling, the
results are identical.  My mission is complete--a way for non-OS3.1 people
to work with the Web without using Win95 to do it.

There is one catch.  You know the $20 a week thing?  I need cash for college
(girls...) and the best way to get it is to sell cool software.  WebView
has...shall I say...a small "slowdown" in the "processing routine", often
adding about a second or two to processing time.  May not seem like a lot,
but when you're constantly reloading the same page, over and over and over,
you'll see the difference.  $10 US is all I ask for.  $10.  Or, as I hope I
can pull off with some other Shareware authors, an "exchange of ideas".
Mainly, a WebView keyfile for a registered piece of your software. That's
it.  Also, if you happen to write HTML editors, and have an ARexx link, be
sure to check out my ARexx port.  Its identical to AMosaic in running.  Not
too hard to support really.

Well, that's all.  Enjoy your HTML.creation.

  @{"Main Menu" link "Main" 0}
  @{"Requirements" link "Req" 0}
@endnode

@node "Req" "Requirements"
WebView was built for non-OS3.1 operating systems, so it will run, with all
its options going, on any OS2.x system.  Haven't tried 1.3, but how could
you get on the 'Net with 1.3?

WebViewPrefs also runs on OS2.x systems.

You'll also need an HTML or Text Editor.  Might I recommend WebPlug by
Esteve Boix, the only HTML editor that runs on my computer?

Another handy thing is @{"StartMenu by John Corigliano" link "SMSupport" 0}.  WebView does some
nifty things with SM, and its the envy of all Win95 users out there.  My
life has changed for the better with this App.

  @{"Main Menu" link "Main" 0}
  @{"Introduction" link "Intro" 0}
  @{"Installation" link "Install" 0}
@endnode

@node "Install" "Installation"
Installation is REALLY easy now.  I figured out Installer.Script (finally!)
and wrote a simple little program to install everything.  Its really rather
easy.  Easy.  Lets put it this way--if you're reading this, you did it all
right.  Aren't you proud?

  @{"Main Menu" link "Main" 0}
  @{"Requirements" link "Req" 0}
  @{"Usage" link "Use" 0}
@endnode

@node "Use" "Usage"
How do you use this puppy?  Well...

* Running WebView

Click the icon.  Then click it again.  Be sure the clicks are spaced apart
no longer than the double-click setting in IPrefs.

Shell-friendly?  Just type "WebView" with no parameters.

* Using WebView

There are several places you can click on the WebView screen:

  Title Bar
    Move WebView to the back.  Hit Left Amiga-A to move it back (Amos...)
  Left Button
    Load An HTML File
  Center Button
    Reload An HTML File
  Right Button
    Quit WebView
  Scroll Bar
    Move Up & Down the Document
  Size Button In Lower-Right
    Change Between Interlaced & Non-Interlaced

    WARNING:  Some OS3.x systems do not get along with Amos Interlace.  If
it doesn't work,
    DON'T DO IT!!!

* How to load Inlined Images

Convert any GIFs or JPEGs to IFF files with this name:

  <original file>.iff

So, if your file was called:

  merchant.jpg

To use it in WebView, convert it to an IFF called:

  merchant.jpg.iff

WebView will load it and compress the converted picture into a file called:

  <original file>.pack

* StartMenu Options

You lucky SM User!  To use the WebView SM functions, you need "SMRexx"
running.  Two buttons will be placed on the Taskbar, one called "WebView
Reload" and one next to the clock.  The Reload button causes all the
computers in the universe to come to a screeching halt (no it reloads the
document, silly!) and the one by the clock flips back to Amos' WebView
display.

  @{"Main Menu" link "Main" 0}
  @{"ARexx Support" link "Rexx" 0}
  @{"Installation" link "Install" 0}
@endnode

@node "Rexx" "ARexx Port"
Are you a Programmasaurus Rexx?  Do you live to control all your
applications through Mr. Hawes interprocess communication protocol,
originally used on IBMs and then ported to a more worthy computer?  You're a
lot sharper than I am, then!

WebView opens up a port called WEBVIEW.1.  If you're a Mosaic user, these
commands will seem familiar:

  GET <filename>
    Load <filename> into WebView
  RELOAD
    Reload the current file

Exciting, huh?

  @{"Main Menu" link "Main" 0}
  @{"StartMenu Support" link "SMSupport" 0}
  @{"Usage" link "Use" 0}
@endnode

@node "SMSupport" "StartMenu Support"
If you haven't noticed by now, I owe much gratitude to John Corigliano.  Not
only does he have a cool first name, and use a cool brand of computer, he
wrote the most useful piece of software on my machine...StartMenu.  It was
one of the few things I enjoyed about Win95 (that and the pinball game on
Plus!...) and was glad I could find it and program for it so easily.

Here's his homepage.  Trust me, once you use StartMenu, you'll throw out any
other AppWindow, AppIcon, AppListview, AppCheckbox, AppPointer, and
AppFileRequester you use now:

  http://www.del.net/users/mopp/

  @{"Main Menu" link "Main" 0}
  @{"Why Amos Rocks and Sucks" link "Eaten" 0}
  @{"ARexx Port" link "Rexx" 0}
@endnode

@node "Tags" "Tags Supported"
OK, so you want to know what Netscape and IE viewers will se that you see as
well?  Here's a list of my greater HTML.processing accomplishments:

  Color Fonts <font color=(color)>
    WebView will find the closest color to (color) in its palette for
    displays
  Backgrounds <body background=(file)>
    Easy...a tiled inline image
  Bgcolor, Text, and Link Settings <body bgcolor=(clr) text=(clr)
                                    link=(clr)>
    See Color Fonts
  Aligned Inlined Images <img align=(left|right)>
    The margins work much more accurately now in WV2.  Really neat tag!
  Form Inputs <input type=(something)>
    Pictures for each type of form
  Tables <table><tr><td></td></tr></table>
    My best accomplishment.  Unlike IE and Netscape, who resize tables to
    fit the text, I resize text to fit the tables.  That text isn't
    going to boss me around no more!!
  Header Fonts <h1></h1>
    Slick, Slick, Slick!  I'm really glad I added them.

Of course, every other basic tag is supported as well.  Just load some pages
you made (or downloaded from the 'Net) and check out how well it works.  You
will be impressed, I guarantee it.

  @{"Main Menu" link "Main" 0}
  @{"Ode To StartMenu" link "SMSupport" 0}
  @{"Why Amos Rocks And Sucks" link "Eaten" 0}
@endnode

@node "Eaten" "Why Version 2 So Quickly?"
Why?  You want to know "why"?!?  How dare you!

No, I'll tell.  Amos, in all truth, is the language you love to hate.  It is
the best of all Basics out there (even Visual) and I am very impressed by
its plethora of functions.  But, its so bug-ridden that even Terminix
couldn't kill them all.  WebView 1 met an untimely end when I tried to add
Header Fonts to it.  It wouldn't compile.  It go halfway through
compilation, right to one of the new lines, and locked up the comupter.
[shrug]

That's why I had to kick the old version's buttocks.  And, if you used the
old one, you will agree that the buttocks were kicked very hard.

So, to François Lionet, master of Klik'n'Play, creator of Amos, I hate you
for killing WebView 1, but can tolerate your PC ventures because of WebView
2.  I salute you with crossed fingers behind my back.

  @{"Main Menu" link "Main" 0}
  @{"Supported Tags" link "Tags" 0}
  @{"Credits" link "Creds" 0}
@endnode

@node "Creds" "Credits"
OK, let me first say that, if I mentioned some copyrighted, trademarked
thing in this document, I don't own that copyright.  With all the suing and
infringement over the 'Net, I don't want to become a blurb on Headline News
for being the latest case.  You still own it.  Stop fuming.  Relax.  That's
good.

Should I @{"thank John Corigliano" link "SMSupport" 0} any more?  Nah.

Should I @{"bash François Lionet" link "Eaten" 0} any more?  I could, but that would get this
document a TVM rating.

All my buddies on the Amos List had a part in this, as well.  They get
mentioned in the credits.

Notable people are Paul Hickman, the Easylife guy, and Pietro Ghizzoni for
the GUI Extension.  It finally works!

The WebCleaner fonts are owned by Andrew Graham.  He also told me that Amiga 
Format had WebView on there.  If anyone has this issue and wouldn't mind 
parting with it, please tell me!  NOW!!

Piracy of the registered version will lead to execution.  Of my plan to
discontinue WebView alterations.  Live with Version 2 as Version 3 (the old
on being eaten by Amos), with Frames, Working Forms, and 'Net access is used
on one computer alone...mine.

Well, that's about it.  Oh, thanks to Microsoft for a good comparison as to
how good WebView really is.  When the same document, on two drastically
different computers, look the same, I'm impressed.

